\section{Related Work}

\subsection{传统光场深度估计方法 (Traditional Light Field Depth Estimation Methods)}

Traditional light field depth estimation methods primarily rely on epipolar plane image (EPI)s, focal stacks, and multi-view stereo techniques. These approaches significantly depend on the global Lambertian reflectance assumption. They assume multi-view photo-consistency across different angular perspectives. Consequently, these methods achieve notable accuracy in ideal, diffuse scenes. However, their mathematical models inherently restrict generalization in complex environments.

Wanner et al. \cite{wanner2014} proposed a foundational depth estimation method based on epipolar plane image (EPI) analysis. They extract depth information by calculating the gradient and slope of epipolar lines. The geometric relationship between the slope of epipolar lines and the corresponding depth is mathematically formulated based on the focal length and spatial-angular baselines. This structure tensor approach effectively captures linear epipolar structures. It yields precise depth maps for texture-rich Lambertian regions. Nevertheless, specular highlights disrupt the continuous epipolar lines. This disruption causes severe slope miscalculations and depth discontinuities.

To complement epipolar geometry, Tao et al. \cite{tao2013} introduced a depth computation method combining focal stacks with defocus cues. They synthesize focal stacks by shifting and summing angular views. The depth is inferred by maximizing the focus measure across different refocus depths. Unlike epipolar slope analysis, this technique exploits the depth-dependent blur characteristics. It demonstrates robustness in weakly textured areas where epipolar gradients vanish. However, the defocus response severely degrades near reflective surfaces. Specular reflections introduce view-dependent shifts that violate the shift-invariant blur model.

In the realm of multi-view stereo, Wang et al. \cite{wang2015} developed a traditional approach relying on multi-view photo-consistency. Chen et al. \cite{chen2017} further extended this by introducing occlusion-aware geometric constraints. They construct a cost volume by evaluating the variance of pixel intensities across multiple viewpoints. The optimal depth is selected by minimizing this photo-consistency cost. This stereo matching strategy explicitly enforces geometric constraints among angular views. It successfully mitigates occlusion artifacts in complex Lambertian scenes. In contrast, the photo-consistency assumption completely fails on non-Lambertian materials. View-dependent specularities yield high variance costs at incorrect depth hypotheses.

Despite their mathematical elegance, these traditional methods share critical limitations. According to physical reflection models \cite{blinn1977}, surface reflectance comprises diffuse and specular components. However, traditional methods severely rely on the global Lambertian reflectance assumption. In non-Lambertian regions, the multi-view photo-consistency assumption inevitably fails. This failure leads to severe depth calculation deviations or large holes. Second, manually designed physical models struggle with complex mixed-material scenes. They lack fine-grained quantification capabilities for pixel-level roughness and deflection vector fields. Finally, these methods cannot decouple non-Lambertian components from the physical optical level. They fail to analyze bidirectional reflectance distribution function parameters or wave-vector representations. Consequently, their generalization ability under complex illumination is extremely poor, highlighting the inherent rigidity of fixed physical models in handling diverse and complex material properties.

\subsection{基于深度学习的极平面图与局部视角方法 (Deep Learning-based EPI and Partial-View Methods)}

Deep learning approaches have extensively adopted epipolar plane image (EPI)s for light field depth estimation. Shin et al. \cite{heber2018} proposed EPINet, a foundational fully-convolutional baseline. This method extracts epipolar features along four primary directions. It concatenates these directional EPIs to infer depth maps. EPINet achieves considerable accuracy in texture-rich Lambertian regions. However, it significantly relies on a sparse angular sampling strategy. This design restricts the angular utilization rate to approximately $34.6\%$. Consequently, the network suffers from severe directional rigidity and angular under-sampling.

To improve feature representation, subsequent studies explored spatial-angular decoupling mechanisms. Lyu et al. \cite{lyu2022} developed deep convolutional architectures that disentangle spatial and angular EPI features. These methods apply separate convolutional kernels to capture local spatial textures and angular slopes. This decoupling strategy significantly reduces computational complexity while enhancing linear epipolar structure extraction. Nevertheless, these architectures still depend on predefined directional EPI slices. They fail to capture the continuous angular variations across the entire light field. This limitation inherently bounds the theoretical upper limit of depth estimation precision.

Addressing the challenges of complex reflectance, recent works \cite{li2021, zhang2023} introduced attention-based feature aggregation to suppress non-Lambertian artifacts. These models dynamically weight local angular views to mitigate specular highlight interference. Wang et al. \cite{wang2023} further explored robust correspondence learning to handle noisy angular signals. They achieve robust depth prediction in scenes with moderate reflections and occlusions. Despite these improvements, these purely data-driven networks lack explicit physical optical modeling. They implicitly suppress non-Lambertian signals without decoupling the underlying material properties. This omission leads to blurred depth features and smoothing artifacts in highly reflective regions.

In summary, existing EPI and partial-view methods exhibit three critical limitations. First, traditional EPI architectures typically utilize only partial views (e.g., four directions), yielding an angular utilization rate of merely $34.6\%$. This causes severe angular under-sampling and directional rigidity, limiting the theoretical precision upper bound. Second, purely data-driven networks lack explicit modeling of non-Lambertian physical properties. When processing reflective and complex texture regions, this deficiency leads to blurred depth features, contrast degradation, and smoothing artifacts. Third, due to insufficient utilization of full-angle information, networks struggle to capture complete coherence variations of non-Lambertian regions across different views. This results in inadequate reasoning capabilities for highlight edges and depth discontinuities. These limitations underscore the poor generalization of purely data-driven paradigms when confronted with complex physical optical phenomena.

\subsection{基于深度学习的物理感知与全角度建模方法 (Deep Learning-based Physics-Aware and Full-Angle Modeling Methods)}

\textbf{Physics-Aware Material Cue Integration.}
To mitigate the violations of photo-consistency, recent approaches integrate physical reflection priors into depth inference networks. For instance, Li et al. \cite{li2021} propose a material-aware architecture that combines material classification cues with dual epipolar features. This method explicitly predicts material masks to guide the depth regression process, achieving notable improvements on non-Lambertian datasets. By decoupling diffuse and specular components, the network partially alleviates highlight-induced artifacts. However, such cue integration often treats material properties as discrete semantic labels rather than continuous physical parameters, limiting the network's ability to model complex micro-surface reflections and subtle roughness variations.

\textbf{Full-Angle Cost Volume Modeling.}
To overcome the angular under-sampling issue, full-angle cost volume architectures have been proposed to aggregate information from all available viewpoints. Standard full-angle cost volumes substantially assume strict photo-consistency across all angular views. While effective for Lambertian scenes, this assumption severely degrades in the presence of specularities. To address this, recent cost volume-based networks, such as MACVO-Net, attempt to substantially overcome the angular under-sampling by incorporating multi-scale cost aggregation. Despite these architectural advancements, the underlying cost metrics still struggle to differentiate between geometric occlusions and non-Lambertian reflectance variations, leading to erroneous depth estimations at material boundaries.

\textbf{Global Summary and Motivation.}
In conclusion, existing light field depth estimation methods face a critical dilemma. Traditional approaches suffer from the rigidity of fixed physical models, which fail to generalize across diverse and mixed-material scenes. Conversely, deep learning-based methods exhibit poor generalization due to their purely data-driven nature, lacking explicit physical constraints to handle non-Lambertian reflectance and full-angle coherence. Unlike previous works that rely on either rigid physical assumptions or black-box data-driven feature extraction, our approach bridges this gap by introducing a dual-mask physical material perception mechanism integrated within a full-angle explicit cost volume architecture. This unified framework effectively decouples complex material properties while preserving full-angle geometric consistency, enabling robust depth estimation in highly reflective and complex environments. Building on these foundational insights, we next introduce our proposed architecture, which explicitly addresses the Lambertian assumption bottleneck through a novel multi-scale angular formulation.

