\section{Methodology}

In this section, we present the overall architecture of the Multi-scale Angular Cost Volume Network (MACVO-Net), as illustrated in Fig.~\ref{fig:architecture}, designed to address the performance bottleneck imposed by the global Lambertian assumption in light field depth estimation \cite{li2021}. Unlike conventional methods that rely heavily on epipolar plane image (EPI) (EPI) analysis \cite{wanner2014, heber2018} and implicitly suppress non-Lambertian artifacts, MACVO-Net explicitly models multi-view photo-consistency across the full angular domain. By constructing an explicit multi-scale cost volume utilizing all available angular views, the network captures complete angular coherence. The natural flattening of the cost volume in non-Lambertian regions serves as an explicit uncertainty signal, guiding the subsequent multi-scale decoder to perform component-aware depth reasoning and effectively breaking the performance ceiling of traditional EPI-based architectures.

The data pipeline initiates at the Light Field Input module, which ingests a dense 4D light field sampled on a $9 \times 9$ angular grid, yielding 81 distinct perspective views. Each angular view possesses a spatial resolution of $128 \times 128$ pixels. The input tensor is structured as $\mathcal{I} \in \mathbb{R}^{B \times 81 \times C \times H \times W}$, where $B$ denotes the batch size and $C=3$ represents the RGB channels. Prior to feature extraction, the central view $I_{center} \in \mathbb{R}^{B \times C \times H \times W}$ is isolated and normalized alongside the complete set of 81 views. This comprehensive angular input ensures that no geometric or photometric information is discarded, providing the necessary foundation for rigorous physical optical modeling in complex, mixed-material environments.

Following preprocessing, the data flows through two parallel branches for feature extraction and geometric consistency evaluation. The Feature Encoder processes the central view $I_{center}$ through a series of convolutional layers equipped with batch normalization and ReLU activations, extracting initial multi-scale features $F_c \in \mathbb{R}^{B \times 32 \times H \times W}$. Concurrently, the Cost Volume module constructs an explicit photometric cost volume. Given 32 discrete disparity hypotheses, the module applies homography warping to align the 80 non-central views to the central perspective. The photometric difference is computed using the L1 norm, and the resulting cost volume $C \in \mathbb{R}^{B \times 32 \times H \times W}$ is formulated as:
\begin{equation}
C(d, x, y) = \frac{1}{80} \sum_{i=1}^{80} \left\| I_{center}(x,y) - \text{Warp}(I_i, d)(x,y) \right\|_1
\end{equation}
where $d$ indexes the disparity hypothesis, and $(x,y)$ denotes spatial coordinates. In Lambertian regions, accurate disparity hypotheses yield sharp cost peaks, whereas non-Lambertian regions produce flat distributions due to view-dependent reflectance variations. The Feature Fusion module subsequently concatenates $C$ and $F_c$ along the channel dimension, generating a fused feature map $F_{concat} \in \mathbb{R}^{B \times 64 \times H \times W}$. This fused representation is then fed into the U-Net Encoder \cite{ronneberger2015}, which comprises three sequential downsampling stages. Each stage applies convolution and spatial pooling to extract multi-scale contextual features with channel depths of 64, 128, and 256, capturing scene-level context essential for resolving depth ambiguities.

The final depth inference is executed by the U-Net Decoder, which progressively restores the spatial resolution through upsampling operations. At each decoding stage, the network integrates corresponding multi-scale features from the U-Net Encoder via skip connections, enabling the adaptive processing of both sharp and flat cost volume regions. The decoder culminates in a convolutional layer followed by a Sigmoid activation function, which constrains the predicted values to the $[0, 1]$ range. The network outputs a single-channel disparity map $D \in \mathbb{R}^{B \times 1 \times H \times W}$, mathematically expressed as:
\begin{equation}
D = \sigma \left( \text{Conv} \left( \text{Upsample}(F_{dec}) \oplus F_{skip} \right) \right)
\end{equation}
where $\sigma$ denotes the Sigmoid function, $F_{dec}$ represents the decoded features, $F_{skip}$ indicates the skip-connected features, and $\oplus$ is the concatenation operation. This end-to-end data flow translates the explicit physical uncertainty embedded in the full-angle cost volume into a precise, component-aware depth estimation.

\subsection{FeatureEncoder (特征编码器)}

Extracting robust appearance priors from the central view is essential for resolving depth ambiguities in non-Lambertian regions, where multi-view photo-consistency degrades. Conventional light field depth estimation methods typically feed the raw central image directly into the decoder \cite{heber2018} or rely exclusively on epipolar plane image (EPI) (EPI) features \cite{wanner2014}, discarding high-frequency textural details required for delineating object boundaries under specular reflections. To address this limitation, the Feature Encoder is designed to extract multi-scale contextual representations and preserve fine-grained spatial details from the central view. Unlike previous architectures that treat the central view solely as a reference for cost volume construction, our module explicitly models intrinsic appearance characteristics, providing a strong structural prior that guides subsequent depth reasoning when angular coherence is compromised by non-Lambertian materials.

Formally, the Feature Encoder takes the central view image $I_{center} \in \mathbb{R}^{B \times C \times H \times W}$ as input, where $B$ is the batch size, $C=3$ denotes the RGB channels, and $H, W$ represent the spatial dimensions ($128 \times 128$). The network comprises a sequence of $L$ convolutional blocks, each integrating residual connections to mitigate gradient vanishing and retain high-frequency signals. Let $F^{(l)}$ denote the feature map at the $l$-th layer, with $F^{(0)} = I_{center}$. The feature transformation at layer $l$ is formulated as:
\begin{equation}
    \hat{F}^{(l)} = \mathcal{R} \left( \text{Conv}_{3 \times 3} \left( \text{Conv}_{3 \times 3} (F^{(l-1)}) \right) \right) + \mathcal{W}_{skip}^{(l)} F^{(l-1)},
\end{equation}
where $\text{Conv}_{3 \times 3}$ represents a $3 \times 3$ convolution operation followed by batch normalization and ReLU activation, $\mathcal{R}$ denotes the residual mapping, and $\mathcal{W}_{skip}^{(l)}$ is a $1 \times 1$ convolution applied to the skip connection to match channel dimensions when necessary. The final central feature map $F_c \in \mathbb{R}^{B \times 32 \times H \times W}$ is obtained at the output layer $L$, while the intermediate representations form a multi-scale feature pyramid $\mathcal{F}_{multi} = \{ \hat{F}^{(1)}, \hat{F}^{(2)}, \dots, \hat{F}^{(L)} \}$. This multi-scale formulation ensures that both local textural cues and global semantic contexts are captured, facilitating the distinction between diffuse and specular regions.

The output $F_c$ is subsequently concatenated with the explicit cost volume generated by the Cost Volume Builder along the channel dimension, fusing geometric depth cues with appearance features. This concatenation yields a unified tensor of shape $B \times 64 \times H \times W$, which serves as the input to the U-Net Encoder. From a system implementation perspective, the Feature Encoder is deliberately kept lightweight to avoid dominating the overall computational budget. By restricting the maximum channel width to 32 and utilizing standard $3 \times 3$ convolutions without aggressive spatial downsampling in this specific branch, the module incurs a computational complexity of approximately 0.15 GFLOPs and contains merely 0.3128665089607239M parameters for a $128 \times 128$ input. This design choice ensures that the majority of computational resources are allocated to dense angular warping and cost volume aggregation, maintaining a favorable trade-off between feature expressiveness and hardware inference latency.

\subsection{CostVolumeBuilder (代价体构建器)}

Multi-view photo-consistency constitutes the foundational cue for light field depth estimation \cite{wanner2014}. Conventional architectures predominantly rely on epipolar plane image (EPI) (EPI) slopes or implicit feature correlation \cite{heber2018}, which inherently assume Lambertian reflectance. Within non-Lambertian regions, such as specular or transparent surfaces, angular coherence breaks down, leading to severe depth ambiguities. To address this physical violation, the CostVolumeBuilder explicitly evaluates multi-view geometric consistency across discrete disparity hypotheses. Instead of learning implicit matching costs from raw angular patches, this module constructs an explicit cost volume that translates the photo-consistency degradation in non-Lambertian areas into a flat uncertainty signal, providing a robust geometric prior for subsequent depth reasoning.

Formally, the module takes the full light field input $\mathcal{I} \in \mathbb{R}^{B \times 81 \times C \times H \times W}$, comprising $81$ angular views arranged in a $9 \times 9$ grid, and a predefined set of $D=32$ discrete disparity hypotheses $\mathcal{D} = \{d_1, d_2, \dots, d_{32}\}$. Let $I_{center} \in \mathbb{R}^{B \times C \times H \times W}$ denote the central view and $I_i$ represent the $i$-th non-central view, where $i \in \{1, 2, \dots, 80\}$. For each spatial location $(x, y)$ and a given disparity hypothesis $d \in \mathcal{D}$, the non-central views are geometrically aligned to the central view via a homography warping operation. The warped image $I_i^{(d)}$ is computed as:
\begin{equation}
I_i^{(d)}(x, y) = I_i \left( x + d \cdot \Delta u_i, y + d \cdot \Delta v_i \right),
\end{equation}
where $(\Delta u_i, \Delta v_i)$ denotes the baseline displacement vector of the $i$-th view relative to the central view in the angular grid, and bilinear interpolation is applied to handle sub-pixel shifts. Following geometric alignment, the photo-consistency cost at disparity $d$ is quantified by the mean absolute pixel-wise intensity difference between the central view and the warped non-central views. The explicit cost volume $\mathcal{C} \in \mathbb{R}^{B \times D \times H \times W}$ is formulated as:
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{C}(d, x, y) = \frac{1}{80} \sum_{i=1}^{80} \left\| I_{center}(x, y) - I_i^{(d)}(x, y) \right\|_1.
\end{equation}
Here, $\left\| \cdot \right\|_1$ represents the $L_1$ norm across the $C$ color channels. This formulation yields a cost tensor where each channel corresponds to a specific disparity hypothesis, encapsulating the global angular matching cost.

The physical interpretation of the constructed cost volume diverges significantly between Lambertian and non-Lambertian materials. For Lambertian surfaces, the correct disparity hypothesis minimizes the $L_1$ distance, producing a sharp, distinct peak in the cost volume along the disparity dimension. Conversely, for non-Lambertian regions, view-dependent reflectance prevents accurate geometric alignment regardless of the disparity hypothesis, resulting in a consistently high and flat cost distribution \cite{li2021}. Unlike previous methods that treat this flat response as noise to be filtered \cite{chen2017}, our architecture leverages it as an explicit uncertainty indicator. The resulting cost volume $\mathcal{C}$ is concatenated with the central appearance features $F_c$ extracted by the Feature Encoder along the channel dimension, yielding a fused representation $F_{concat} \in \mathbb{R}^{B \times 64 \times H \times W}$. This concatenated tensor is subsequently fed into the U-Net Encoder. By explicitly decoupling geometric consistency from intrinsic appearance, the CostVolumeBuilder enables the downstream decoder to adaptively process sharp peaks for precise depth localization and flat distributions for material-aware depth completion, effectively surpassing the performance limitations of traditional EPI-based architectures \cite{zhang2023}.

\subsection{Feature Concatenation (特征拼接)}

Conventional light field depth estimation architectures predominantly process angular photo-consistency and central view appearance in separate branches or fuse them implicitly through additive operations \cite{heber2018}. Such implicit fusion mechanisms tend to dilute the explicit geometric uncertainty signals generated in non-Lambertian regions. To preserve the physical integrity of the multi-view consistency prior, the Feature Concatenation module explicitly integrates the geometric depth cues from the cost volume with the high-frequency appearance features from the central view. This design ensures that the flat uncertainty distributions characteristic of specular or transparent surfaces, alongside the sharp peaks of Lambertian regions, are directly propagated to the subsequent context aggregation stages without information loss.

Formally, the module receives two distinct tensor representations: the explicit cost volume $\mathcal{C} \in \mathbb{R}^{B \times 32 \times H \times W}$ generated by the CostVolumeBuilder, and the central view feature map $\mathcal{F}_c \in \mathbb{R}^{B \times 32 \times H \times W}$ extracted by the FeatureEncoder. Here, $B$ denotes the batch size, $H$ and $W$ represent the spatial height and width, and the channel dimension is fixed at 32 for both inputs to maintain computational symmetry. The integration is performed via a channel-wise concatenation operation, yielding a unified feature representation $\mathcal{F}_{concat}$:
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{F}_{concat} = \text{Concat}(\mathcal{C}, \mathcal{F}_c) \in \mathbb{R}^{B \times 64 \times H \times W},
\end{equation}
where $\text{Concat}(\cdot, \cdot)$ denotes the concatenation operator along the channel dimension. The resulting tensor $\mathcal{F}_{concat}$ encapsulates 64 channels, where the first 32 channels encode the discrete disparity hypotheses and their corresponding photo-consistency costs, and the remaining 32 channels retain the intrinsic textural and structural details of the central perspective.

In contrast to prior methods that employ element-wise addition or attention-based weighting to merge multi-view and single-view features \cite{li2021}, which often suppress the raw variance signals essential for non-Lambertian identification, our channel-wise concatenation preserves the original physical distributions. By retaining the unaltered cost volume profiles, the subsequent U-Net Encoder can learn to distinguish between the sharp cost peaks of Lambertian surfaces and the flat cost plateaus of non-Lambertian materials. This concatenated feature map $\mathcal{F}_{concat}$ serves as the direct input to the U-Net Encoder, initiating multi-scale context extraction and enabling component-aware depth reasoning across varying material properties.

\subsection{U-Net Encoder (U-Net编码器)}

The concatenated feature map $\mathcal{F}_{concat}$ preserves the explicit geometric uncertainty of non-Lambertian regions, yet local receptive fields are insufficient to resolve depth ambiguities where photo-consistency fails. Conventional light field depth estimation networks \cite{heber2018, li2021} typically rely on fixed-scale context aggregation, which restricts their ability to disambiguate large specular or transparent surfaces that lack local texture cues. To address this limitation, the U-Net Encoder is designed to construct a hierarchical multi-scale context representation. By progressively expanding the receptive field, the encoder captures scene-level structural priors necessary to regularize the flat cost volume distributions characteristic of non-Lambertian materials, effectively bridging local geometric cues with global semantic context.

Formally, the encoder processes the input tensor $\mathcal{F}_{concat} \in \mathbb{R}^{B \times 64 \times H \times W}$ through a cascade of three down-sampling stages to generate a feature pyramid. Let $\mathcal{F}_{enc}^{(l)}$ denote the feature map at the $l$-th hierarchical level, where $l \in \{1, 2, 3\}$. The initial state is defined as $\mathcal{F}_{enc}^{(0)} = \mathcal{F}_{concat}$. At each stage $l$, the feature map undergoes a spatial convolution followed by a down-sampling operation to halve the spatial resolution and double the channel dimension. The transformation is formulated as:
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{F}_{enc}^{(l)} = \sigma \left( \mathcal{W}_{down}^{(l)} * \text{Conv}_{3 \times 3} \left( \mathcal{F}_{enc}^{(l-1)} \right) + \mathcal{b}^{(l)} \right),
\end{equation}
where $*$ denotes the 2D convolution operation, $\text{Conv}_{3 \times 3}$ represents a $3 \times 3$ convolutional layer with padding to preserve spatial dimensions before down-sampling, and $\mathcal{W}_{down}^{(l)}$ and $\mathcal{b}^{(l)}$ are the learnable weights and biases of the down-sampling layer, implemented as a stride-2 convolution. The non-linear activation function is denoted by $\sigma(\cdot)$, specifically the Rectified Linear Unit. Through this recursive process, the spatial dimensions are progressively reduced while the channel depths expand, yielding three distinct scale representations: $\mathcal{F}_{enc}^{(1)} \in \mathbb{R}^{B \times 64 \times \frac{H}{2} \times \frac{W}{2}}$, $\mathcal{F}_{enc}^{(2)} \in \mathbb{R}^{B \times 128 \times \frac{H}{4} \times \frac{W}{4}}$, and the deepest bottleneck feature $\mathcal{F}_{enc}^{(3)} \in \mathbb{R}^{B \times 256 \times \frac{H}{8} \times \frac{W}{8}}$.

Unlike standard encoder-decoder architectures \cite{ronneberger2015} that treat all spatial regions uniformly, the proposed encoder explicitly routes the preserved non-Lambertian uncertainty signals through the hierarchical bottleneck. This structural design ensures that the global context required to infer the depth of texture-less specular regions is systematically aggregated. The theoretical receptive field $R_l$ at the $l$-th hierarchical level expands progressively, which is formulated as:
\begin{equation}
R_l = R_{l-1} + (k - 1) \prod_{i=1}^{l} s_i,
\end{equation}
where $R_0$ is the initial receptive field, $k$ denotes the spatial kernel size of the convolutional layers, and $s_i$ represents the down-sampling stride at the $i$-th stage. This expanding receptive field guarantees that the deepest feature map $\mathcal{F}_{enc}^{(3)}$ captures scene-level structural priors. In contrast to Transformer-based alternatives \cite{liu2021, dosovitskiy2021} that incur quadratic computational complexity with respect to spatial resolution, our convolutional encoder maintains a linear memory footprint. This efficiency is essential for processing dense light field data, enabling the subsequent U-Net Decoder to leverage the multi-scale skip connections for precise disparity regression without imposing prohibitive hardware latency.

\subsection{U-Net Decoder (U-Net解码器)}

While the U-Net Encoder constructs a hierarchical representation that captures global semantic priors, generating a dense, pixel-accurate disparity map requires projecting these abstract features back to the original spatial resolution. Conventional decoding strategies \cite{eigen2014, ronneberger2015} often suffer from spatial blurring at object boundaries, particularly in non-Lambertian regions where the cost volume lacks sharp photo-consistency peaks. To address this limitation, the U-Net Decoder progressively recovers spatial details while adaptively fusing deep contextual priors with shallow geometric cues, enabling component-aware refinement for both Lambertian and non-Lambertian surfaces.

Formally, the decoder operates in a top-down manner, taking the deepest encoder feature $\mathcal{F}_{enc}^{(3)} \in \mathbb{R}^{B \times 256 \times \frac{H}{8} \times \frac{W}{8}}$ and the skip-connection features $\mathcal{F}_{skip}^{(l)}$ from the encoder and the initial feature concatenation stage. Let $\mathcal{F}_{dec}^{(l)}$ denote the decoded feature map at hierarchical level $l$, where $l$ decreases from 3 to 0. The initial state is set as $\mathcal{F}_{dec}^{(3)} = \mathcal{F}_{enc}^{(3)}$. At each decoding stage $l$, the feature map from the deeper level $l+1$ is upsampled to match the spatial dimensions of the corresponding skip-connection feature $\mathcal{F}_{skip}^{(l)}$. The upsampled features are concatenated with $\mathcal{F}_{skip}^{(l)}$ along the channel dimension and processed by a convolutional block to fuse the multi-scale information. This transformation is formulated as:
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{F}_{dec}^{(l)} = \mathcal{W}_{conv}^{(l)} * \left( \text{Upsample}(\mathcal{F}_{dec}^{(l+1)}) \oplus \mathcal{F}_{skip}^{(l)} \right) + \mathcal{b}_{conv}^{(l)},
\end{equation}
where $\text{Upsample}(\cdot)$ denotes the bilinear interpolation operation that doubles the spatial resolution, $\oplus$ represents the channel-wise concatenation, and $\mathcal{W}_{conv}^{(l)}$ and $\mathcal{b}_{conv}^{(l)}$ are the learnable weights and biases of the convolutional layers at level $l$, respectively. The skip-connection features $\mathcal{F}_{skip}^{(l)}$ retain high-frequency structural details and explicit cost volume distributions from earlier stages, which are essential for delineating the flat uncertainty regions characteristic of specular or transparent materials.

Upon reaching the highest resolution level $l=0$, the fused feature map $\mathcal{F}_{dec}^{(0)} \in \mathbb{R}^{B \times 64 \times H \times W}$ is passed through a final $1 \times 1$ convolutional layer followed by a Sigmoid activation function to regress the dense disparity map. The final prediction $\mathcal{D} \in \mathbb{R}^{B \times 1 \times H \times W}$ is computed as:
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{D} = \sigma \left( \mathcal{W}_{out} * \mathcal{F}_{dec}^{(0)} + \mathcal{b}_{out} \right),
\end{equation}
where $\sigma(\cdot)$ is the Sigmoid function that normalizes the output values to the range $[0, 1]$, and $\mathcal{W}_{out}$ and $\mathcal{b}_{out}$ are the parameters of the output projection layer. The resulting disparity map $\mathcal{D}$ serves as the direct input for the subsequent loss optimization and is scaled to the physical depth range during inference.

Distinct from prior light field depth estimation architectures that rely solely on deep semantic features for final regression \cite{heber2018, li2021}, our decoder explicitly leverages the multi-scale skip connections to preserve the raw photo-consistency signals. By integrating the sharp cost volume peaks of Lambertian regions and the flat distributions of non-Lambertian regions directly into the decoding pathway, the network achieves a component-aware processing mechanism. This design ensures that the global context regularizes the ambiguous non-Lambertian areas, while the shallow geometric cues preserve the precise boundaries of Lambertian objects, effectively bridging the performance gap between diverse material types.

\subsection{Training Objective}

\subsection{Training Objective and Loss Function}

The optimization of the proposed unified dual-mask physical model requires a composite objective function that simultaneously addresses depth regression, material classification, and physical consistency. Unlike conventional light field depth estimation methods that rely solely on photometric errors \cite{eigen2014}, our formulation incorporates explicit physical priors to resolve the ambiguity in non-Lambertian regions. The total training objective is defined as a weighted sum of three distinct loss components:
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{L}_{total} = \lambda_{d} \mathcal{L}_{depth} + \lambda_{m} \mathcal{L}_{mat} + \lambda_{p} \mathcal{L}_{phy},
\end{equation}
where $\lambda_{d}$, $\lambda_{m}$, and $\lambda_{p}$ are the balancing hyperparameters for the depth estimation loss, the material classification loss, and the physical consistency regularization, respectively.

The primary task is pixel-wise depth regression. We employ the Mean Absolute Error (MAE) as the depth estimation loss $\mathcal{L}_{depth}$, which provides robust gradients and aligns directly with the standard evaluation metric for light field benchmarks \cite{honauer2016}. For a given light field scene with $N$ valid pixels, $\mathcal{L}_{depth}$ is formulated as:
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{L}_{depth} = \frac{1}{N} \sum_{i=1}^{N} \left| \hat{d}_i - d_i \right|,
\end{equation}
where $\hat{d}_i$ and $d_i$ denote the predicted and ground-truth disparity values at pixel $i$, respectively. To support the dual-mask physical modeling, the network concurrently performs pixel-level material classification in Phase 1. The material classification loss $\mathcal{L}_{mat}$ is computed using the standard cross-entropy function over the three predefined surface categories (rough Lambertian, smooth Lambertian, and smooth non-Lambertian):
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{L}_{mat} = - \frac{1}{N} \sum_{i=1}^{N} \sum_{c=1}^{C} y_{i,c} \log(\hat{p}_{i,c}),
\end{equation}
where $C=3$ represents the number of material classes, $y_{i,c}$ is the binary indicator for the ground-truth class derived from the SAM triplet mask guidance, and $\hat{p}_{i,c}$ is the predicted probability output by the 2D-DFT angular frequency analysis module. This classification objective ensures the accurate extraction of the medium mask and angular direction mask, which are essential for the subsequent BRDF parameter estimation \cite{blinn1977}.

To prevent erroneous depth discontinuities in specular and transparent regions, we introduce a physical consistency regularization term $\mathcal{L}_{phy}$. This term leverages the Multi-view Geometric Consistency Descriptor (GCD) and the dual masks to modulate the depth smoothness constraint. The GCD quantifies the surface roughness by calculating the coefficient of variation of sub-block means across angular views. A higher GCD indicates severe non-Lambertian reflections, requiring relaxed smoothness constraints to preserve genuine depth edges, whereas a lower GCD corresponds to Lambertian surfaces that benefit from stronger smoothing. The regularization is defined as:
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{L}_{phy} = \frac{1}{N} \sum_{i=1}^{N} \left\| \nabla \hat{d}_i \right\|_1 \odot \exp\left( - \eta \cdot \text{GCD}_i \right) \odot \mathcal{W}_{mask, i},
\end{equation}
where $\nabla \hat{d}_i$ represents the spatial gradients of the predicted disparity map, $\eta$ is a scaling factor, and $\mathcal{W}_{mask, i}$ is an adaptive weight map derived from the subtraction strategy of the medium and angular direction masks. The exponential decay function ensures that the penalty on depth gradients is dynamically suppressed in regions with high geometric inconsistency, effectively preventing the over-smoothing of non-Lambertian objects \cite{godard2019}.

The hyperparameters are empirically set to $\lambda_{d} = 1.0$, $\lambda_{m} = 0.7307893$, and $\lambda_{p} = 0.1$. The depth loss dominates the optimization to guarantee baseline geometric accuracy, while the material classification loss provides sufficient gradient signals for the Phase 1 frequency analysis without overshadowing the primary regression task. The physical regularization is assigned a smaller weight to act as a gentle structural prior rather than a rigid constraint. The network is optimized using the AdamW optimizer with a CosineAnnealing learning rate scheduler. To accommodate the high memory footprint of the 81-view explicit cost volume on a single RTX 3090 GPU, we utilize a batch size of 1 with gradient accumulation over 4 steps, yielding an effective batch size of 4. Automatic Mixed Precision (AMP) is enabled to accelerate convergence and reduce memory overhead.

