\section{Experiments}

To comprehensively evaluate the proposed Unified Dual-Mask Physical Model and validate its capability in breaking the global Lambertian assumption, we construct a diverse and challenging light field dataset corpus. Unlike previous studies that predominantly rely on purely diffuse datasets, our curated collection explicitly incorporates non-Lambertian and mixed-material scenes. This design is essential for rigorously testing the model's physical material perception mechanism and component-aware depth estimation under complex optical conditions. The detailed descriptions of the selected datasets are as follows.

\textbf{Lambertian Datasets.} We include three standard synthetic light field benchmarks: HCInew \cite{honauer2016hci}, HCI-Old \cite{honauer2016hci}, and Wanner\_HCI \cite{wanner2013light}. These datasets primarily consist of scenes with ideal diffuse (Lambertian) surfaces. HCInew contains 44 scenes with complex geometric structures and occlusions. HCI-Old comprises 33 scenes focusing on basic geometric shapes and texture variations. Wanner\_HCI includes 24 scenes with diverse indoor and outdoor environments. All three datasets provide $9 \times 9$ angular views with a spatial resolution of $512 \times 512$, accompanied by precise synthetic ground-truth disparity maps. While these datasets do not contain significant specular or scattering artifacts, they serve as essential baselines to ensure that our physically-driven model does not degrade in performance on traditional, purely Lambertian scenes.

\textbf{Non-Lambertian Dataset.} To directly challenge the global Lambertian assumption, we employ the Non-lambertian\_zhenglong \cite{zheng2020non} dataset, which contains 68 scenes specifically rendered with varying degrees of specular and scattering materials. This dataset includes challenging objects (e.g., David, Teddy, Apple) with adjustable specular ratios (e.g., 10\%, 30\%, 50\%), allowing for a fine-grained evaluation of the model's robustness against highlight-induced feature ambiguities. The angular resolution is $9 \times 9$, and the ground-truth disparity is derived from the rendering engine's depth buffer. This dataset is key for validating the efficacy of our MRI-like angular frequency analysis and dual-mask modeling in decoupling specular components from the underlying geometric structure.

\textbf{Mixed-Material Dataset.} Real-world environments rarely consist of a single material type. Therefore, we incorporate the UrbanLF-Syn \cite{meng2021urbanlf} dataset, comprising 60 complex urban street scenes. These scenes feature a highly heterogeneous mixture of Lambertian (e.g., concrete, asphalt), specular (e.g., glass windows, vehicle bodies), and translucent/scattering materials. With $9 \times 9$ views and $512 \times 512$ spatial resolution, UrbanLF-Syn provides a realistic testbed for evaluating the model's component-aware depth estimation and adaptive energy adjustment mechanisms in highly mixed and unconstrained environments.

\textbf{Data Preprocessing, Augmentation, and Split.} To ensure computational efficiency and uniform input dimensions, all light field images are centrally cropped or resized to a unified spatial resolution of $256 \times 256$. For disparity normalization, we apply a per-scene 2-98 percentile clipping strategy, mapping the valid disparity range to $[0, 1]$, which mitigates the impact of extreme outlier depths and stabilizes the training process. The entire corpus consists of 229 valid scenes, which are partitioned into a fixed training set of 209 scenes and a validation set of 36 scenes. To prevent the model from being biased toward the majority Lambertian class during optimization, we implement a domain-balanced sampling strategy utilizing a \texttt{WeightedRandomSampler} with inverse frequency weighting. Furthermore, data augmentation is performed via random horizontal flipping, which is strictly and consistently applied across all 81 angular views to preserve the epipolar geometry and multi-view consistency. A comprehensive summary of the dataset statistics is provided in Table~\ref{tab:datasets}.

