\section{Conclusion}

In this paper, we presented a unified dual-mask physical model to address the primary bottleneck of the global Lambertian assumption in light field depth estimation. By explicitly modeling the underlying optical physics of non-Lambertian and mixed materials, the proposed framework transitions from implicit artifact suppression to rigorous component-aware depth inference. The integration of physical material perception, adaptive energy adjustment, and full-angle geometric consistency effectively resolves the multi-view photo-consistency violations caused by specular and scattering reflections.

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Physical Material Perception via Dual-Mask and Angular Frequency Analysis:} We formulated a dual-mask physical model comprising a medium mask for pixel-level roughness quantification and an angular direction mask for deflection vector field recording. Coupled with an MRI-like 2D-DFT analysis on $9 \times 9$ angular samples, this mechanism classifies material components based on spectral energy distribution. A reverse wavevector parsing framework enables component-aware depth estimation, achieving an 88.235294\% material classification accuracy and replacing the global Lambertian restriction with a physically interpretable optical model.
    \item \textbf{Adaptive Energy Adjustment Guided by Geometric Consistency:} We introduced the Geometric Consistency Descriptor (GCD), which quantifies surface multi-view consistency and physical roughness via the coefficient of variation. Combined with a dual-subtraction strategy and SAM ternary mask guidance, this mechanism adaptively adjusts the energy map based on the directional alignment between the GCD and energy distributions. This process resolves feature ambiguity in complex textures and reflective regions, enhancing feature contrast and eliminating specular artifacts to provide reliable depth priors.
    \item \textbf{MACVO-Net with Full-Angle Explicit Cost Volume:} We developed MACVO-Net to construct an explicit multi-scale cost volume utilizing all 81 angular views and 32 disparity hypotheses, bypassing the partial-view EPI paradigm. The multi-scale decoder leverages the naturally flat cost volume in non-Lambertian regions as an explicit uncertainty signal to guide spatial propagation. This architecture achieves complete angular information utilization, overcoming the directional rigidity of EPIs and yielding an overall validation MAE of 0.3128665089607239 with reduced parameter complexity.
\end{itemize}

The integration of physical optics with data-driven representation learning establishes an effective paradigm for complex light field analysis. Subsequent investigations will extend this physical modeling framework to dynamic light field sequences and sparse angular sampling configurations, expanding its utility in practical 3D vision systems.
